theorem interior_closure_interior_closure_interior_closure
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] (A : Set X) :
    interior (closure (interior (closure (interior (A : Set X))))) =
      interior (closure (interior (A : Set X))) := by
  apply Set.Subset.antisymm
  ·
    -- First inclusion: `interior (closure (interior (closure (interior A))))`
    -- is contained in `interior (closure (interior A))`.
    have h :
        closure (interior (closure (interior (A : Set X))))
          ⊆ closure (closure (interior (A : Set X))) := by
      -- `interior (closure (interior A)) ⊆ closure (interior A)`.
      have h₁ :
          interior (closure (interior (A : Set X)))
            ⊆ closure (interior (A : Set X)) := interior_subset
      -- Taking closures preserves inclusions.
      exact closure_mono h₁
    -- Taking interiors preserves inclusions as well.
    exact interior_mono h
  ·
    -- Second inclusion: `interior (closure (interior A))`
    -- is contained in `interior (closure (interior (closure (interior A))))`.
    have h :
        closure (interior (A : Set X)) ⊆
          closure (interior (closure (interior (A : Set X)))) :=
      Topology.closure_interior_subset_closure_interior_closure_interior
        (A := A)
    exact interior_mono h

import Mathlib
import Aesop

namespace Topology

variable {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X]

/--  A corrected proof that  
`interior (closure (interior (closure A))) = interior (closure A)`. -/
theorem interior_closure_interior_closure (A : Set X) :
    interior (closure (interior (closure (A : Set X)))) =
      interior (closure (A : Set X)) := by
  -- We prove the two inclusions separately.
  apply Set.Subset.antisymm
  ·
    -- `interior (closure (interior (closure A)))` is contained in
    -- `interior (closure A)` because the set inside the first `interior`
    -- is contained in the one inside the second `interior`.
    have h₁ :
        closure (interior (closure (A : Set X))) ⊆ closure (A : Set X) := by
      -- `interior (closure A)` is contained in `closure A`.
      have hInt : interior (closure (A : Set X)) ⊆ closure (A : Set X) :=
        interior_subset
      -- Taking closures preserves inclusions.
      exact closure_mono hInt
    -- Taking interiors preserves inclusions.
    exact interior_mono h₁
  ·
    -- Conversely, `interior (closure A)` is contained in
    -- `interior (closure (interior (closure A)))`.
    -- First, note that `interior (closure A)` is contained in the closure
    -- of `interior (closure A)` (by `subset_closure`).
    have h₁ :
        interior (closure (A : Set X)) ⊆
          closure (interior (closure (A : Set X))) :=
      subset_closure
    -- Again, taking interiors preserves inclusions.
    have h₂ :
        interior (interior (closure (A : Set X))) ⊆
          interior (closure (interior (closure (A : Set X)))) :=
      interior_mono h₁
    -- Finish by rewriting `interior (interior (closure A))`.
    simpa [interior_interior] using h₂

end Topology

theorem interior_closure_eq_univ_iff_closure_eq_univ
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    interior (closure (A : Set X)) = (Set.univ : Set X) ↔
      closure (A : Set X) = (Set.univ : Set X) := by
  classical
  constructor
  · intro hInt
    -- `interior (closure A)` is contained in `closure A`.
    have hSub : interior (closure (A : Set X)) ⊆ closure (A : Set X) :=
      interior_subset
    -- Using `hInt`, we obtain `univ ⊆ closure A`.
    have hLeft : (Set.univ : Set X) ⊆ closure (A : Set X) := by
      simpa [hInt] using hSub
    -- Trivially, `closure A ⊆ univ`.
    have hRight : closure (A : Set X) ⊆ (Set.univ : Set X) := by
      intro _ _; trivial
    exact Set.Subset.antisymm hRight hLeft
  · intro hClos
    -- Rewrite the left‐hand side using `hClos` and simplify.
    simpa [hClos, interior_univ]
